cae.description: This cycling aerobic interval set is intended to prepare the athlete for the specific intensity and stress of half and full Ironman racing. The Zone 2 intervals should be done at the expected intensity of the athlete's next half or full Ironman. For new athletes, this will be low to mid Zone 2. For more experienced athletes, this intensity will take place in upper Zone 2. For advanced athletes, these intervals can even include Zone X, a rare exception to the 80/20 system.

cai.description: Anaerobic Intervals Rides are designed to increase aerobic capacity, or the ability to use oxygen to power your cycling. Aim to complete each 3-minute Interval at an output you could sustain for 15 minutes in race circumstances, which equates to an initial RPE of 7 on a 1-10 scale.

can.description: When executed properly, this anaerobic interval set is the most effective method at increasing an athlete's VO2max. While VO2max is only one component an athlete's success, it is a direct predictor of endurance performance. Additionally, VO2 intervals have been proven to be more effective at improving overall economy than submaximal (threshold) or supramaximal intervals. Thus, a successful integration of these intervals in the General phase of training places the athlete in an advantageous position for the upcoming Specific phase, and ultimately their endurance performance results. These intervals are challenging, and the athlete must take great care to not perform them at a Zone 3 or Zone 5 intensity. The unusually high rest period compared to a Zone 3 work reflects the difficulty of the interval. The 80/20 principle is fundamental to executing these anaerobic intervals, as the athlete has deliberately trained easy 80% of the time in order to have the form necessary to maintain this repeated Zone 4 intensity. These anaerobic intervals are permission to go very hard. Be bold, but measured. A successful anaerobic interval set will have the athlete's output (pace, speed, power) be almost identical for each interval, in Zone 4, and without fade.

cap.description: Aerobic Progression Rides are designed to develop intensive endurance by exposing cyclists to a large volume of work at a range of moderate intensities.

cci.description: Muscular endurance is arguably the most important ability an endurance athlete can develop, and no other interval improves muscular endurance better than the cruise interval. The application of the cruise interval is broad. The only interval type appropriate for both the General and Specific phase of training, its benefit spans all triathlon distances. The 80/20 principle makes the cruise interval possible, by ensuring the athlete is sufficiently rested in order to achieve the required Zone 3 intensity. The cruise interval is the antithesis of Zone X. A successful cruise interval set has the output for each interval nearly identical to the previous, while maintaining solid Zone 3 intensity. Consider reducing the rest time from 3 minutes to 2 minutes and then 2 minutes to 1 minute if previous cruise intervals sets have been successful.

ccp.description: Critical Power Rides feature longer intervals at an intensity that walks the line between moderate and high. They are designed to enable athletes to maintain a stable metabolic state at higher intensities.

cd.description:
While not originally designed to promote fat loss, Depletion Rides do provide this benefit.
A Depletion Ride is essentially an Endurance Ride that is performed in a calorie-restricted state. Do this ride on an empty stomach and consume only water and electrolytes during it--no calories.

cdi.description: Developed by scientists at the University of Udine in Italy, Descending Intervals are proven to increase the amount of time an athlete is able to spend above 90% of VO2max intensity within a single session. This makes the workout a potent way to boost aerobic capacity (aka VO2max).

cf.description: Discipline is required for the cycling foundation set. If rested, the temptation is to drift into Zone X. However, save your energy for the 20% of the 80/20 plan, and stay in Zone 1-2 for this workout. High cadence. Avoid group cycling that will tempt you to go beyond Zone 2.

cfa.description: Fast Finish Rides train the body to counter the natural tendency to slow down with fatigue. They're also a good way to administer a small dose of harder cycling when appropriate.

cff.description: One of the few workouts designed with the intensity scheduled for the end of the workout, the intent is to expose the athlete to high intensity while slightly fatigued.

cfo.description: Because the cycling force intervals are so short, the athlete will have to often use perceived effort to gauge intensity, as HR may not reach Zone 5 prior to the interval ending. This workout is an excellent time to go very hard, but aim to have each interval with a similar output and avoid fading near the end of the interval. If hills are unavailable, the athlete can simulate by reducing cadence to 65-75rpm and occasionally standing.

cir.description: Sprint Intervals Rides will not make you a faster sprinter, but they will improve your pedaling efficiency and your ability to resist fatigue at higher intensities. Studies have shown that even ultra-endurance cyclists benefit from including some Zone 5 work in their training.

cmi.description: An exceptionally challenging workout. Half and full Ironman athletes may question the necessity for the suffering caused by this particular workout, but the raw increase in FTP will pay off in subsequent workouts and on race day. Used only in the General phase for half and full Ironman, it (unfortunately) spans into the Specific phase for Spring and Olympic training. Pacing is critical in the first Zone 3 interval, start in low Zone 3 and work your way up.

cpi.description: This workout format was developed by scientists at the University of Copenhagen in the 2010's and found to improve race performance in trained recreational  athletes. It features 1-minute intervals in which the first 30 seconds are completed in Zone 3, the next 20 seconds in Zone 4, and the last 10 second in Zone 5. You then go straight back to the top and complete the same sequence four times more for a total of five repetitions before easing down to Zone 1 for recovery.

cpr.description: Power Repetitions Rides are designed to develop explosive power on the bike, which comes in handy in a variety of situations, such as grinding through soft mud on a mountain bike and punching the accelerator to drop other riders on the road.

cre.description: Take advantage of this day with active recovery. Avoid even Zone 2. High cadence.

csp.description: Mixed Intervals Rides are designed to give athletes maintenance-level exposure to a broad spectrum of intensities. They work well in base training, during recovery weeks, and as a secondary workout in peak training periods when the primary workout is more challenging and race-specific.

csr.description: Today's Sprint Intervals Rides features shorter Zone 5 efforts than the one you did in Week 1.

css.description: Steady State Rides target Zone X, a zone that is generally avoided in the 80/20 system but is good to spend SOME time in, as doing so builds a bridge between extensive endurance (the ability to ride far) and intensive endurance (the ability to ride fast without fatiguing).

ct.description: The cycling tempo workout does an excellent job at muscular endurance, and should be used as a method to either verify or re-establish current HR Zones. A difficult workout, pacing is key. Start slightly lower and finish stronger. Some brief forays into Zone 4 are acceptable.

ctr.description: Threshold Rides feature extended efforts in Zone 3. They are a proven way to increase the lactate threshold (LT) and improve performance at a wide range of race distances.

ctt.description: Follow the protocol described in the "Cycling Power" section of this document to establish/ update your cycling power training zones:

cvi.description: Variable-Intensity Interval Rides feature an unusual two-step interval format that is proven to enable athletes to spend more time at or near VO2max intensity than they do in traditional, single-pace intervals. The result is bigger gains in aerobic capacity/VO2max.

cvo.description: VO2max Intervals Rides are designed to increase aerobic capacity, or the ability to use oxygen to power your cycling. Aim to complete each 2-minute Interval at an output you could sustain for 6 minutes in race circumstances, which equates to an initial RPE of 7-8 on a 1-10 scale.

ec.description: As the name suggests, Endurance Rides serve to develop build basic endurance by developing its various physiological and psychological elements, which include fat-burning capacity and mental focus.

ezc.description: Easy Rides are the most important type of ride you can do and are the ride type you should do most frequently in training. Collectively, they serve to develop aerobic fitness, endurance, efficiency, and durability, and enable you to perform better in and get more benefit from your more challenging workouts.

lic.description: Lactate Intervals Rides are designed to boost aerobic capacity (aka VO2max), which is the most important physiological underpinning of cycling performance. This particular format was developed by exercise scientists at Inland Norway University as a way to increase the amount of time an athlete is able to spend near VO2max intensity within a single session without becoming exhausted.

ouc.description: Over/Under Intervals Rides feature intervals in which the intensity fluctuates between slightly above and slightly below the lactate threshold (LT). The harder segments target Zone Y, which occupies the small space between Zone 3 and Zone 4, while the easier segments target Zone 3, whose upper limit aligns with LT.

er.description: As their name suggests, Endurance Runs serve to develop the basic physiological and psychological ingredients of endurance, including fat-burning capacity and mental focus.

erff.description: Fast Finish Endurance Runs serve two main functions. Physically, they offer all the benefits of a regular Endurance Run, developing the basic physiological and psychological ingredients of endurance, including fat-burning capacity and mental focus. But the fast-finish element confers an additional benefit in the form of pacing skill development. Runners who struggle with pacing tend to pace their longer runs in such a way that they are tired and slowing down toward the end. Fast Finish Endurance Runs encourage you to hold back a little more in the early part of the run so you're able to speed up slightly at the end.

lfr.description: A Long Fartlek Run is just what it sounds like: a long run and a fartlek run mashed together. This type of workout is useful when you've already built the basic endurance you need to go the distance in your next race and it's now time to work on the ability to run fast with fatigue in the legs. Today's Long Fartlek Run targets Zone 4.

lir.description: Lactate Intervals Runs are designed to boost aerobic capacity (aka VO2max), which is the most important physiological underpinning of running performance. This particular format was developed by exercise scientists at Inland Norway University as a way to increase the amount of time an athlete is able to spend near VO2max intensity within a single session without becoming exhausted.

our.description: Over/Under Intervals Runs feature intervals in which the intensity fluctuates between slightly above and slightly below the lactate threshold (LT). The harder segments target Zone Y, which occupies the small space between Zone 3 and Zone 4, while the easier segments target Zone 3, whose upper limit aligns with LT.

r.description: 10K Pace Intervals offer essential practice at race pace during 10K training but are also a useful fitness builder in training for shorter and longer events.

ra.description: Developed by influential French exercise physiologist Veronique Billat, Accelerations Runs combine the unique physical challenge of running at every pace between a jog and a full sprint with a unique and valuable pacing challenge.

rae.description: This running aerobic interval set is intended to prepare the athlete for the specific intensity and stress of their upcoming event. The Zone 2 intervals should be done at the expected intensity of the athlete's next race. For new athletes, this will be low to mid Zone 2. For more experienced athletes, this intensity will take place in upper Zone 2. For advanced athletes, these intervals can even include Zone X, a rare exception to the 80/20 system.

rcv.description: Critical Velocity Runs feature longer intervals at an intensity that rides the line between moderate and high. They are designed to enable runners to maintain a stable metabolic state at faster paces.

rd.description: Today's Depletion Run is 5 minutes longer than last week's.

rdi.description: Developed by scientists at the University of Udine in Italy, Descending Intervals are proven to increase the amount of time an athlete is able to spend above 90% of VO2max intensity within a single session. This makes the workout a potent way to boost aerobic capacity (aka VO2max).

rf.description: Discipline is required for the running foundation set. If rested, the temptation is to drift into Zone X. However, save your energy for the 20% of the 80/20 plan, and stay in Zone 1-2 for this workout. Avoid running with individuals who will tempt you to exceed Zone 2.

rff.description: One of the few workouts designed with the intensity scheduled for the end of the workout, the intent is to expose the athlete to high intensity while slightly fatigued. An excellent simulation of a strong race finish.

rfr.description: Today's Fartlek Run is a slightly more challenging version of the one you did last week.

rhm.description: Half-Marathon Pace Runs offer essential practice at race pace during half-marathon training, but are also a useful fitness builder in training for shorter and longer events.

rhr.description: Because the run hill repeats are so short, the athlete will have to often use perceived effort to gauge intensity, as HR may not reach Zone 5 prior to the interval ending. This workout is an excellent time to go very hard, but aim to have each interval with a similar output and avoid fading near the end of the interval. If hills are unavailable, a treadmill is recommended. If neither option is available, the prescribed intensity and duration can still be met.

rl.description: Similar to the frequent Run Foundation workout, the Long Run is instead measured by distance to ensure the athlete experiences the required stress. Consider performing these workouts using similar terrain, apparel, and nutrition you expect on race day. Brief periods of walking are acceptable for workouts greater than 20 miles. Complete this workout by distance only, any planned time associated with this workout is a broad estimate

rlff.description: This workout is designed to teach the athlete's body and brain to resist and manage fatigue, placing the most stress at the very end of the workout. Half and full marathon athletes may benefit from a rare Zone X exception and replace some of the Zone 2 time with Zone X. Complete this workout by distance only, any estimated planned time or TSS associated with this workout is a broad estimate.

rlms.description: The Marathon Simulator is intended to introduce the athlete to the specific stress, pacing nutrition, clothing and terrain of race day. Pre-workout meal and preparation should simulate the environment of race day as much as possible. The course for this workout should be similar in nature to the marathon race course. Pacing should measured to negative split the 16 miles. Complete this workout by distance only, any estimated planned time or TSS associated with this workout is a broad estimate.

rls.description: Speed Intervals Runs will not make you a faster sprinter, but they will improve your running economy and your ability to resist fatigue at faster speeds. Studies have shown that even ultrarunners benefit from including some speed intervals in their training.

rlsp.description: A successful execution of this workout would have the pace of the Zone 3 intervals remain steady or slightly increase throughout the activity. You may be cursing Matt and David by the end of the intervals, but you'll be praising them on race day. Complete this workout by distance only, any estimated planned time or TSS associated with this workout is a broad estimate.

rmi.description: Complex in execution, the reward is high. This workout is best done pre-programmed into a watch (such as a Garmin).

rmp.description: Marathon Pace Runs are intended to help runners become more efficient and comfortable at marathon pace (MP).They can also be used outside of marathon training to provide an endurance stimulus that's more challenging than a standard long run.

rp.description: Similar to Fast Finish Runs, Progression Runs teach the body to run faster on tired legs. This Progression Run features a three-step progression that hits the following intensities:

rpf.description: Developed by coach Jay Johnson, Progression Fartlek Runs are designed to develop intensive endurance by exposing runners to a large volume of work at a range of moderate intensities. Progression Fartlek Runs are also an effective tool for developing pacing skill because they require runners to go against their instincts and sustain faster paces for longer stretches of time as the workout goes on.

rpi.description:
80/20 Endurance
This workout format was developed by scientists at the University of Copenhagen in the 2010's and found to improve race performance in trained recreational runners. It features 1-minute intervals in which the first 30 seconds are completed in Zone 3, the next 20 seconds in Zone 4, and the last 10 second in Zone 5. You then go straight back to the top and complete the same sequence four times more for a total of five repetitions before easing down to Zone 1 for recovery.

rre.description: "Recovery Run" is a bit of a misnomer. These relatively short, low-intensity runs don't actually accelerate recovery from previous training. Rather, they offer a gentle training stimulus that doesn't INTERFERE with recovery from prior training.

rsi.description: Unlike the very similar running hill repeats (RHR) the running short interval is done on a flat surface. Feel free to go hard.

rsp.description: Not to be confused with the Zone 5 running short interval (RSI), running speed play is done in Zone 4 with much shorter recoveries. If done in Zone 5, the athlete will fade.

rss.description: Steady State Runs target Zone X, a zone that is generally avoided in the 80/20 system but is good to spend SOME time in, as doing so builds a bridge between extensive endurance (the ability to run far) and intensive endurance (the ability to run fast without fatiguing).

rt.description: The running tempo workout does an excellent job at muscular endurance, and should be used as a method to either verify or re-establish current HR Zones. A difficult workout, pacing is key. Start slightly lower and finish stronger. Some brief forays into Zone 4 are acceptable.

rta.description: Brief, but fast intervals to promote the taper.

rtt.description: A Relaxed Time Trial is a time trial that is run at 95% of race effort. These workouts serve to enhance goal-specific fitness and build confidence.

rvi.description: Variable-Intensity Interval Runs feature an unusual two-step interval format that is proven to enable athletes to spend more time at or near VO2max intensity than they do in traditional, single-pace intervals. The result is bigger gains in aerobic capacity/VO2max.

rvo.description: VO2max Intervals are designed to increase aerobic capacity, or the ability to use oxygen to power your running. Aim to complete each 2-minute VO2max Interval Maximal Aerobic Speed, or at a pace you could sustain for 6 minutes in race circumstances, which equates to the upper end of Zone 4 and an initial perceived effort rating of 7-8 on a 1-10 scale.

rxt.description: You have the option to either run or perform an aerobic cross-training session. Either way you will complete 20 minutes of exercise at low intensity.

rzx.description: This workout includes a rare use of Zone X in the 80/20 system. Zone X is considered moderate intensity, which falls in the "20" of 80/20 running. Normally, Zone 3 and higher are used to build speed, but Zone X fits very nicely into Ultra distance training where speed plays a lesser role to endurance. While you won't race in Zone X for an Ultra, these long sessions of Zone X will make you tough as nails.

wr.description: Walk/Runs are very useful when your body is not ready to handle straight running. Whether you're just starting out as a runner or you're returning from an injury, Walk/Runs serve as an efficient bridge to straight running.

rrps.description: Recovery Runs + Strides are used primarily to prime the body for a hard run the next day--either a race or a key workout. The combination of steady Zone 1 running and brief bursts at Zone 5 gets the body ready for a big effort without causing fatigue.

heart.description: This workout was designed to help us correlate swim paces with swim heart rates so that we can create heart-rate based swim workouts to complement our existing pace-based swim workouts.

sae.description: For half and full Ironman athletes, these intervals can be used to simulate the intensity of race day swimming at upper Zone 2, with perhaps some intensity in Zone X. For Sprint and Olympic athletes, best to keep these at mid Zone 2, and use the more intense Zone 3+ workouts to prepare for racing.

sci.description: Designed to increase Critical Velocity, these intervals are done at upper Zone 3. Be careful not to get sloppy, form should not be sacrificed for what feels like more power. These are an excellent way to test different techniques, as the athlete can compare the effect of slight conscious changes to the swim stroke on each interval.

se.description: Endurance Swims feature a sustained, steady effort in Zone 2. They serve to develop aerobic fitness, endurance, and efficiency, and enable you to perform better in and get more benefit from your more challenging workouts.

sf.description: For half and full Ironman athletes, these workouts can be used to simulate the intensity of race day swimming at upper Zone 2, with perhaps some intensity in Zone X. For Sprint and Olympic athletes, best to keep these at mid Zone 2, and use the more intense Zone 3+ workouts to prepare for racing.

sis.description: Sprint Intervals Swims improve swim efficiency and the ability to resist fatigue at faster speeds.

sli.description: Lactate Intervals Swims develop aerobic capacity, or the ability to turn oxygen into speed in the water.

smi.description: Consider using different strokes for this workout. The purpose is intensity, and therefore the athlete is not limited to freestyle.

sre.description: Consider using multiple strokes for this recovery swim. Easy pace.

ssi.description: This extremely high intensity and frequency will test your ability to maintain form at high speed.

ssp.description: This set should ultimately help improve Critical Velocity, and provide a significant challenge that helps the workout fly by!

st.description: The "big brother" of the swim cruise interval (SCI), take care not to start too fast and fade. Target your Z3 Critical Velocity and hold on to your form.

sta.description: If possible, in open water at the race venue or similar environment. Brief, but fast intervals to promote the taper.

sti.description: Threshold Intervals Swims develop intensive endurance, or the ability to sustain faster speeds comfortably.

stt.description: This set is designed to confirm or reestablish your Critical Velocity. Suppose you swim your four-hundred-yard test in 5:55 (5.92 minutes) and your two-hundred-yard test in 2:50 (2.83 minutes). Your critical velocity, then, is (400m  200m)  (5.92 min.  2.83 min.) = 64.7 m/ min. It is customary to express critical speed in the form of time per hundred yards. To make this conversion, divide one hundred by your critical velocity. In this example, 100  64.7 = 1.55, or 1 minute 33 seconds.
